Recommended book lists: 
It can be hard to find good books for the children to read. These are books that we have personally enjoyed, and in the next few days we will release book lists for elementary grades. 


Pre-K: 
-  Margaret Wise Brown – Goodnight Moon. (Chosen because of its place in literature. It is a children’s classic.)
-  Eric Carle – The Hungry Caterpillar. (Chosen for its introductions of counting.)
-  Eric Carle – The Very Quiet Cricket. (Chosen because this tiny little cricket will not chirp until he finds his kin. I personally like to add that he is a boy cricket, and that the other little cricket is a girl cricket that surely must be quite beautiful.) 
-  Dr Seuss – Thidwick the Moose. (The author is definitely not our guy, but this book does have a good message, taken on its own: carrying the weight of racial strangers will lead to your demise.)
-  D’aulaires’ Book of Animals. (This book inspires a love of nature, and the realization that certain animals live in their own place, because it is where they live healthily.) 
-  D’Aulaire –Children of the Northlights. I recommend this book because of its connection to our kinfolk. 
-  Aesop’s Fables (Especially The Farmer and the Snake). Recommended edition: The Aesop for Children, with pictures by Milo Winter, 1993. The fables can be used for literature lessons in Kindergarten, and usually have a great moral message. They are great to start exercising your children’s narration skills: read the story and have them narrate it back to you. 
-  Sartore / Alexander – Animal Ark. Beautiful pictures of animals that hopefully will inspire a love for nature. 
-  Pallotta – Construction Alphabet (a board book). This is for the mothers of boys. Introduce letters in a fun way: with construction equipment.  
-  Mother Goose’s Nursery Rhymes. Easy, light rhymes to inspire a love for poetry. 
-  Montessori – Letter Work. Recommended by a subscriber, seconded by me. A nice way of introducing phonics to little ones, with sandpaper texture so those tots can trace those letters. 
-  Sneed Collard - The Deep-Sea Floor. A picture book about all the creatures that live in the deep sea. Good to fill your child’s mind with mystery and beauty.
-  George Lincoln Rockwell – Fable of the Ducks and the Hens. This story tells how the naïve ducks had their happy lives wrecked by pushy (((hens))). A very appropriate story to tell your children repeatedly.

K  through 2nd *PART 2 OF 3*

-  Gertrude Warner – The Boxcar Children. Only let your children read this if you are ready for homemade forts in your yard. This book is also recommended for the 3rd and 4th graders. 
-  E.B. White – Charlotte’s Web. A book about a friendly spider and a Pig’s friendship, and a little girl’s desire to protect a farm pet she has come to love. The book values friendship and strong commitments. This book is also recommended for the 3rd and 4th graders.
-  Laura Ingalls Wilder – Little House in the Big Woods. This series is not for everyone, some children will find it dull and unentertaining. However, the stories are wholesome and one ought to have given it a try. This book is also recommended for the 3rd and 4th graders.
-  Margery Williams – The Velveteen Rabbit. The premise is that if you love a toy for a very long time, it will become real. This book teaches us that hardships are a normal part of life, and that they will come to pass. Read this book with your children. 
-  Jennie Hall – Viking Tales. This is a Landmark book. The Landmark books are great historical novels, based on real stories from long ago. They are written by an expert in the specific field being discussed, for example: Jennie Hall has written many books on the early ages Vikings. This specific book tells the tales of Eric the Red, Leif the Lucky, Harold of Norway and others. It is a good and worthy read. This book is also recommended for the 3rd and 4th graders.
-  Rudyard Kipling – Just so Stories. Some children will find this book dull and unentertaining, but this book explains why whales eat smaller preys, how the kangaroos got long legs and a tail, and other animal stories. 
-  Thornton Burgess – The Burgess Bird Book for Children. A narrative book telling stories of Jenny Wren, and many other bird friends. It shows actual characteristics of birds. Some children will find this book dull and unentertaining. 
-  James Herriot – Treasury for Children. Your children will grow up good and kind if you show them to love and take care of animals. This book helps with that. It will make you feel good. Use this for the early ages as a read-aloud. This book is also recommended for the 3rd and 4th graders.
-  Robert Louis Stevenson – A Child’s Garden of Verses. Gentle verses and rhymes which can help improve your child’s language skills. 
-  Hans Christian Andersen – Andersen Fairy Tales. More classic fairy tales teaching your child about their cultural heritage. These things matter. 
-  Richard Atwater – Mr. Popper’s Penguins. This is a funny story. Your child might learn a thing or two about penguins, and about the difference between the North and the South Pole. 
-  Robert Browning – The Pied Piper of Hamelin. Classic fairy tale about a town plagued by rats, and the townsfolk hires the pied piper to rid them of the vermin. The pied piper fulfills his job, but when the townsfolk refuses to pay him, he abducts the children and they are never seen again. Use this as a lesson for your children to not go with creepy guys with a flute, and also to teach them the importance of honor. 
-  Rachel Firth - Usborne Illustrated Classics for Boys. This book is now out of print, and you can find it used on Thriftbooks or Abebooks fairly easily. It’s a great copy with the stories you want your boys to swoon over, and in our case it inspired one of our sons at an early age to actually want to read thick books. The stories are those of Robin Hood, Gulliver, and four others. The book’s ISBN is 978-0794524395, in case you have a difficult time finding it.
